    utdelingFritakTitle:'Participation exemption (Tax Act § 2-38)',
    utdelingFritakBody:'Dividends and capital gains <b>between companies</b> are generally tax-free under the participation exemption. A holding company can receive dividends from a subsidiary without paying tax — the dividend tax only kicks in when profits are passed on to a <i>personal</i> shareholder. The calculator above shows that final step.',
    utdelingFritakLink:'Read more about the participation exemption →',
    utdelingIntro:'This calculator shows the combined tax burden when profits are distributed to the owner. For <b>AS</b> (shareholder model): corporate tax 22% + dividend tax 37.84% = <b>51.5%</b> effective rate. For <b>sole prop.</b> (enterprise model): ordinary income 22% + national insurance 10.8% + bracket tax = up to <b>50.6%</b> marginal rate. The symmetry principle ensures the business form itself provides no tax advantage.<br><br><i style="font-size:12px;opacity:.7">The sole prop. view is a simplified pedagogical illustration — actual tax is also affected by personal allowance and minimum deduction.</i>',
